    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-11-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-11-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="372"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.00/11–154</note>
                <head>No. 372<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the <gloss type="from">Special
                            Assistant</gloss> to the President for National Security Affairs
                            (<persName corresp="#p_CR1" type="to">Cutler</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d372fn1">The source text is headed: “Meeting in the
                        President’s Office.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>eyes only</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-11-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 1, 1954—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Present:</head>
                    <item>The President, <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF1">J. F. Dulles</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_ARB1"
                            >Anderson</persName>, <persName>Burgess</persName>,<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d372fn2">
                            <persName>Carter L. Burgess</persName>, Assistant Secretary of Defense
                            for Manpower and Personnel.</note>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CR1">Cutler</persName>, and
                            <persName>Goodpaster</persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d372fn3">According to the President’s appointment book,
                                <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName>, <persName
                                corresp="#p_ARB1">Anderson</persName>, and
                                <persName>Burgess</persName> met with the President at 11:30 a.m.
                            for <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName>’s “usual Monday
                            appointment” and were joined at 12:15 p.m. by <persName
                                corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RAAW1"
                                >Radford</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CARB1">Carney</persName>,
                            and <persName corresp="#p_CR1">Cutler</persName>. (<persName
                                corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, White House Central
                            files, “Daily Appointments, 1953–1961”)</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>…<note n="4" xml:id="d372fn4">Ellipsis in the source text.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Tachen Islands:</hi> The <gloss target="#t_CHINCOM1"
                            >ChinCom</gloss> attacked last night one of the smaller islands, with 18
                        aircraft, and killed and wounded a dozen or so of the defending garrison. It
                        is reported that an enemy convoy is being assembled north of a small Tachen
                        Island, 20 thousand yards distant from the largest.</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_CR1">Cutler</persName> assured
                    the President that as the record now stood, there had not been a decision to use
                    American forces for the defense of the Tachen Islands, that <persName
                        corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName> understood that the US would not
                    defend, and was not obligated to defend any offshore islands, that US forces
                    would fight back if attacked. While there are in the Tachen Islands some radar
                    installations, useful for early warning, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> made the point that the Islands were not
                    indispensable.</p>
                <p>It was decided to deflect the <hi rend="italic">Wasp</hi>, so as to obtain an
                    aerial reconnaissance of the facts, probably to accelerate the meeting of the
                    three carriers in the China Sea to November 4, not to push our forces in too
                    close to the Tachens, on the basis of information derived from the
                    reconnaissance to decide whether to have US surface vessels make a friendly
                    visit (as heretofore), or to take some other course of action.</p>
            </div>
